snippet.textDisplay:
Generally speaking....rules for selecting the BEST Japanese restaurants:
1- NO BUFFETS. Buffets are usually lower quality, higher volume for ALL foods, it especially typical for Japanese food where quality and presentation are paramount; not some American face-stuffing attitude toward food.
2- Never eat at a Japanese restaurant that is open 7 days a week. Even more, the best ones may not be open for both lunch and dinner. See Item 1 for explanation.
3 - The best Japanese restaurants specialize in a certain type of food - sushi, ramen, yakitori...again, see Item 1.
4- sometimes applicable but not necessary - a lot of high quality ones (in the US) don’t accept tips. For Japanese, the price is the price; a tip is almost considered an insult. Never tip when in Japan...again, considered an insult.
